'''Moriyama Hachiman-gu''' (守山八幡宮, もりやまはちまん宮) is a Shinto shrine located in Nanbuta, Ogawamachi, Uki City, {{ill|Kumamoto Prefecture|ja|熊本県|qq=draft}}. Under the former Modern Shrine Ranking System, its Rank was Gōsha.

== Overview ==
Situated at the foot of Nichidake (日岳)—the main peak of the Nichidake Mountain Range, which runs nearly north–south and has an elevation of 243 m—this shrine has an ancient origin. Tradition holds that it was once a subsidiary shrine of {{ill|Usa Hachiman Shrine|ja|宇佐神宮|qq=draft}}, but according to one account it was rebuilt as a subsidiary shrine of {{ill|Otokoyama Hachiman Shrine|ja|男山八幡宮|lt=Otokoyama Hachiman Shrine|lt_ja=石清水八幡宮|qq=draft}} in {{ill|1051 AD|ja|1051st year|qq=draft}} (Eishō 6).<ref>{{Cite book|lang=ja|title=『Ogawamachi History』|publisher={{ill|Ogawamachi Town Office|ja|小川町役場|qq=draft}} (Kumamoto Prefecture)|date=1979}}</ref> It is said that between {{ill|1048 AD|ja|1048th year|qq=draft}} (Eishō 3) and {{ill|1051 AD|ja|1051st year|qq=draft}} (Eishō 6) the shrine buildings were constructed, with Takahashi Sōgan, a priest from Otokoyama Hachiman Shrine, serving as governor and overseeing the enshrinement ceremonies.<ref>{{Cite book|lang=ja|title=『Kumamoto Prefectural Encyclopedia』|publisher={{ill|Kumamoto Nichinichi Shimbunsha|ja|熊本日日新聞社|qq=draft}}|date=1982|page=819}}</ref>

Known for the Tetsugan Issai-kyō (the Tetsugan version of the {{ill|Great Canon|ja|大蔵経|qq=draft}}, based on the Huangbo edition), the Edo-period Zen monk {{ill|Tetsugan Dōkō|ja|鉄眼道光|qq=draft}} was born as the son of the shrine priest Saeki Jōshin of Moriyama Hachiman-gu.<ref>{{Cite book|lang=ja|title=『Tetsugan – A Brief Explanation of Doctrines』|publisher={{ill|Kodansha|ja|講談社|qq=draft}}|date=1994|page=9}}</ref> Later, Tetsugan Dōkō himself renamed his birthplace as {{ill|Sambō-ji|ja|三宝寺|qq=draft}}, which now stands adjacent to Moriyama Hachiman-gu.

== Deities ==
* {{ill|Ojin Tennō|ja|応神天皇|qq=draft}}
* {{ill|Jingū Kōgō|ja|神功皇后|qq=draft}}
* {{ill|Hime Ōkami|ja|姫大神|qq=draft}}

=== Merged Shrines ===
* The {{ill|Minamino Shrine|ja|南小野神社|qq=draft}} (a former village shrine) is also merged here. Note that Minamino Shrine merged with {{ill|Kumanoza Shrine|ja|熊野座神社|qq=draft}} in {{ill|1910 AD|ja|1910th year|qq=draft}} (Meiji 43).
** The enshrined deities of Minamino Shrine and Kumanoza Shrine are: {{ill|Isotake no Mikoto|ja|五十猛命|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Ōi-hime no Mikoto|ja|王位姫命|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Izanami-no-Mikoto|ja|伊弉冉命|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Kototoki no Otoko|ja|事解之男命|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Hayatama Otoko|ja|速玉男命|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Jingū Kōgō|ja|神功皇后|qq=draft}}.

== Worship and Belief ==
* The annual festival day is {{ill|October 15|ja|10月15日|qq=draft}}.

== Subordinate Shrines ==
* An Inari shrine dedicated to {{ill|Ukano Mitama-no-Kami|ja|宇迦之御魂神|1=Ukanomitama|2=ja|3=ウカノミタマ|qq=draft}} is located within the shrine grounds.

