== Overview ==
Situated at the foot of Nichidake (日岳)—the main peak of the Nichidake Mountain Range, which runs nearly north–south and has an elevation of 243 m—this shrine has an ancient origin. Tradition holds that it was once a subsidiary shrine of {{ill|Usa Jingū|en|Usa Jingū|qid=Q715632|lt=Usa Hachiman Shrine|1=Usa Jingū}}, but according to one account it was rebuilt as a subsidiary shrine of {{ill|Otokoyama Hachiman Shrine|ja|男山八幡宮|lt=Otokoyama Hachiman Shrine|lt_ja=石清水八幡宮|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Otokoyama Hachiman Shrine|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 石清水八幡宮|1=Iwashimizu Hachimangū|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q710098}} in {{ill|1051|en|1051|qid=Q19363|lt=1051 AD|1=1051}} (Eishō 6).<ref>{{Cite book|lang=ja|title=『Ogawamachi History』|publisher={{ill|Ogawamachi Town Office|ja|小川町役場|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ogawamachi Town Office|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} (Kumamoto Prefecture)|date=1979}}</ref> It is said that between {{ill|1048|en|1048|qid=Q19359|lt=1048 AD|1=1048}} (Eishō 3) and {{ill|1051|en|1051|qid=Q19363|lt=1051 AD|1=1051}} (Eishō 6) the shrine buildings were constructed, with Takahashi Sōgan, a priest from Otokoyama Hachiman Shrine, serving as governor and overseeing the enshrinement ceremonies.<ref>{{Cite book|lang=ja|title=『Kumamoto Prefectural Encyclopedia』|publisher={{ill|Kumamoto Nichinichi Shimbunsha|ja|熊本日日新聞社|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kumamoto Nichinichi Shimbunsha|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 熊本日日新聞|1=Kumamoto Nichinichi Shimbun|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11568194}}|date=1982|page=819}}</ref>

Known for the Tetsugan Issai-kyō (the Tetsugan version of the {{ill|Great Canon|ja|大蔵経|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Great Canon|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 仏典|1=Buddhist texts|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q1001051}}, based on the Huangbo edition), the Edo-period Zen monk {{ill|Tetsugen Doko|en|Tetsugen Doko|qid=Q435294|lt=Tetsugan Dōkō|1=Tetsugen Doko}} was born as the son of the shrine priest Saeki Jōshin of Moriyama Hachiman-gu.<ref>{{Cite book|lang=ja|title=『Tetsugan – A Brief Explanation of Doctrines』|publisher={{ill|Kodansha|en|Kodansha|qid=Q726081|lt=Kodansha|1=Kodansha}}|date=1994|page=9}}</ref> Later, Tetsugan Dōkō himself renamed his birthplace as {{ill|Sambō-ji|ja|三宝寺|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sambō-ji|1=Q11355119|comment=changed title based on wikidata|qid=Q11355119}}, which now stands adjacent to Moriyama Hachiman-gu.

